transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Thanks for calling Viagra, Clint speaking. How can I help you?

Speaker 2: Hi, yeah, the reason for my call is that I canceled my subscription and I sent an email on the 21st.

Speaker 1: I just wanted to confirm that. On the email, it says that—

Speaker 2: Let me take a look, one moment.

Speaker 1: Yeah, no, so it looks like it's still active currently. What was the issue?

Speaker 2: Was there something wrong with the Viagra or—

Speaker 1: Are you getting it too fast? Because you can order this as needed. You don't have to get it every month or automatically.

Speaker 2: No, just not satisfied with the product. That's all. I want to try something else. Well, you know, working—

Speaker 1: I mean, we can always, you know—

Speaker 2: Stop billing you or not send you any more of this, right? And I can send you my newest Viagra from Pfizer from France.

Speaker 1: For free, ten of those?

Speaker 2: See if that's working for you better, and obviously not send you anything else. And so you're able to call me back.

Speaker 1: No, just cancel the whole thing for me. I'm gonna actually go see my doctor and see what my problem is. I—

Speaker 2: Have a feeling there's something other than just using the Viagra. So—

Speaker 1: Okay, I understand, sir, but, you know, we can always give you time to see the doctor as well. There's no rush.

Speaker 2: No, that's okay. For now, I'm okay. You might just cancel my subscription.

Speaker 1: Okay, I'll cancel your subscription. It's understood. Once this is canceled, there's no more refills down the line.

Speaker 2: No more refills, nothing else. If you can send an email confirmation, I will appreciate it.

Speaker 1: No email confirmation, just a verbal answer that your prescription is canceled.

Speaker 2: Okay. Thank you so much.

Speaker 1: You're welcome.
